body:
I put this code in Godbolt.
```rust
pub fn swap1(x: &mut u32, y: &mut u32) {
    *y ^= *x;
    *x ^= *y;
    *y ^= *x;
}

pub fn swap2(x: &mut u32, y: &mut u32) {
    core::mem::swap(x, y)
}

pub fn swap3(x: &mut u32, y: &mut u32) {
    (*x, *y) = (*y, *x);
}

pub fn swap4(x: &mut u32, y: &mut u32) {
    *x ^= *y;
    *y ^= *x;
    *x ^= *y;
}

pub fn swap5(x: &mut u32, y: &mut u32) {
    core::mem::swap(y, x)
}

pub fn swap6(x: &mut u32, y: &mut u32) {
    (*y, *x) = (*x, *y);
}
```
I was surprised to find that every one of these functions is represented individually in the output, even with `-C opt-level=s`. This is most egregious with `swap1`/`swap2`/`swap3` and `swap4`/`swap5`/`swap6` where the exact same instructions are output, but those in turn differ only trivially and could possibly be unified as well.
